Q1: What is the difference between a t-test and a z-test? Provide an example scenario where you would
use each type of test.

ANS. 
A t-test and a z-test are both statistical tests used to determine whether there is a significant difference between two sample means. The main difference between the two tests is that a z-test is used when the population standard deviation is known, whereas a t-test is used when the population standard deviation is unknown.

Example Scenario:

Suppose we want to determine if there is a significant difference between the mean scores of two different groups of students in a math exam. We know the standard deviation of the population from which one group was sampled but not the other.

If we know the population standard deviation, we can use a z-test to determine if the difference in means is statistically significant. On the other hand, if we don't know the population standard deviation, we can use a t-test to determine if the difference in means is statistically significant.
Q2: Differentiate between one-tailed and two-tailed tests.

ANS. In hypothesis testing, a one-tailed test is a statistical test in which the alternative hypothesis is directional. That is, we are testing for the possibility of a difference in only one direction. For example, we might be testing whether a new medication increases the time it takes for people to fall asleep.

On the other hand, a two-tailed test is a statistical test in which the alternative hypothesis is non-directional. That is, we are testing for the possibility of a difference in both directions. For example, we might be testing whether a new medication has an effect on the time it takes for people to fall asleep, but we don't know whether the effect will be an increase or a decrease.

Q3: Explain the concept of Type 1 and Type 2 errors in hypothesis testing. Provide an example scenario for
each type of error.

ANS. In hypothesis testing, there are two types of errors: type 1 and type 2.

A type 1 error occurs when we reject a true null hypothesis. This means that we conclude that there is a significant difference between two sample means when, in fact, there is no such difference. This error is also known as a false positive.

Example: Suppose a pharmaceutical company is testing a new drug to lower cholesterol levels. If they conclude that the drug is effective when it is not, this would be a type 1 error.

A type 2 error occurs when we fail to reject a false null hypothesis. This means that we conclude that there is no significant difference between two sample means when, in fact, there is such a difference. This error is also known as a false negative.

Example: Suppose a pharmaceutical company is testing a new drug to lower cholesterol levels. If they conclude that the drug is not effective when it is, this would be a type 2 error.

Q4: Explain Bayes's theorem with an example.
ANS. Bayes's theorem is a mathematical formula used to calculate the probability of an event occurring based on prior knowledge of the event's probability and new evidence.

The formula for Bayes's theorem is:

P(A|B) = P(B|A) * P(A) / P(B)

where:

P(A|B) is the probability of event A occurring given that event B has occurred.
P(B|A) is the probability of event B occurring given that event A has occurred.
P(A) is the prior probability of event A occurring.
P(B) is the probability of event B occurring.
